gomodel:SYNGO_939  a      owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: The authors use an antibody against the extracellular domain Lasso, a cleaved fragment of teneurin-2 that stays membrane-anchored, for immunoEM of synaptosomes. Fig.4 F,G,I shows the postsynaptic localization.\nThis postsynaptic localization is supported by a biochemical sub-fractionation of synaptosomes shown in Fig.4H.\nFig.3 shows the interaction of Lasso/LPH1 in NBa2 cells which supports a membrane localization of Lasso.\n\n22/6/2017 Pim\n- \"extrinsic component\" --> Teneurin is cleaved after the TMR on the extracellular side. It is therefore not an integral protein. Yet, it stays membrane anchored as show in Figs. 3-5; this is probably through binding to cell surface proteins.\n- Accession Q9R1K2-2 was retrieved by BLAST of human lasso protein sequence against rat uniprot proteins. The best scoring reviewed sequence was selected with match score:\nE-value: 0.0\nScore: 13616\nIdent.: 97.8%\nPositives : 99.1%\nQuery Length: 2637\nMatch Length: 2765\nOne unreviewed sequence (A0A096P6L6) had marginally better score but this seems to endode an equivalent lasso sequence.. Experimental description: rat brain synaptosomes were used for immunoEM and fractionation.\n\nFig.3 used human Lasso: \"Full-length Lasso cDNA (GenBank accession no. JF784339) was reconstructed by conventional cloning from ESTs and fragments obtained by PCR amplification of human\nbrain cDNA (AMS Biotechnology).\" Species is disregarded for annotation." ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0003-0912-1514" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-3670-7863" ;
        dc:date           "2017-10-12" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_CC_939" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10116" .

